******
[2] Dominican Republic (San Cristobal)
Date: Mon 26 Aug 2013
Source: Prensa Latina [edited]
http://www.plenglish.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1798931&Itemid=1


The number of people affected by cholera in the Dominican southern province of San Cristobal increased to 50 percent this weekend [24-25 Aug 2013], medical sources said here Mon 26 Aug 2013.

Doctor Manuel Geraldino, director of the Juan Pablo Pina Hospital, said 17 new cases were hospitalized between Saturday and Sunday [24-25 Aug 2013], the most serious, a woman with 38 weeks of pregnancy. Public Health Vice Minister Rafael Schiffino said the incidence of the outbreak may have its origin in the difficulties for drinkable water supply and the trash recollection.

After more than 100 years of absence, the disease was registered in the Dominican Republic in November 2010, one month after it had appeared in Haiti.

For almost 3 years, 25 000 cases were reported, the last of them at the northern province of Espaillat at the end of 2012.

